<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> General </F>
<H3> <TI>   Li Lanqing Attends Asia-Pacific Trade Fair Opening </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Li Lanqing Attends Asia-Pacific Trade Fair Opening </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW0706114394 Beijing XINHUA in English 1041 GMT 7 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0706114394 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Beijing, June 7 (XINHUA) -- The fifth Asia-Pacific 
International Trade Fair (ASPAT '94) opened at the China 
International Exhibition Center (CIEC) here this morning. 
  Chinese Vice-Premier Li Lanqing, executive secretary of the 
United Nations Economic and Social Commission for Asia and the 
Pacific (UN-ESCAP) Rafeeudin Ahmed, and chairman of the China 
Council for the Promotion of International Trade (CCPIT) Zheng 
Hongye were present at the opening ceremony of the fair, which 
is co-sponsored by CCPIT and UN-ESCAP. 
  The 80,000-square-meter exhibition includes about 3,000 
participants from 30 countries and regions such as China, 
Australia, Bangladesh, Canada, Colombia, Denmark, Germany, 
India, Japan, the Republic of Korea, the Philippines, Russia and 
the United States. 
  Exhibits display light industrial products, mechanical 
equipment, electronics technology, communications equipment and 
products, environmental protection facilities, high-tech and 
patented products, jewelry, ornaments, garments, traditional 
handicrafts, and real estate projects. 
  During the fair, five symposiums will also be held on the 
electronics trade, China's current economic situation and 
investment environment, China's reform of its foreign trade 
system and investment policies, and China's financial and 
taxation reforms. 
  The Philippines and Hong Kong have sent large trade 
delegations to the fair to conduct business talks. 
  ASPAT '94 is aimed at demonstrating economic achievements in 
the region, highlighting economic and trade complementarity and 
potential, promoting economic development and cooperation 
throughout the Asia-Pacific region and with other countries in 
the world, and exploring ways for strengthening cooperation and 
jointly achieving prosperity among the Asia-Pacific countries in 
a new world situation. 
  ASPAT was first proposed in 1962 by the United Nations Asia 
and Far East Economic Commission, which is the present UN-ESCAP. 
  The first three ASPAT fairs were held in 1966, 1969 and 1972 
in Thailand, Iran and India, and proved to be fruitful. The 
fourth ASPAT fair, which was held in Beijing in 1985, was also a 
complete success. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

