<F P=100> Northeast Asia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Jiang Zemin Says China To Play `Positive' Role </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Jiang Zemin Says China To Play `Positive' Role </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   HK0706132394 Hong Kong AFP in English 1301 GMT 7 June 94 </F>
<F P=103> HK0706132394 </F>
<F P=104>  Hong Kong AFP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Beijing, June 7 (AFP)--Chinese President Jiang 
Zemin assured an Association of Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN) 
delegation here Tuesday that China would take a "positive role" 
in dealing with the North Korea nuclear crisis. Jiang told the 
head of the multinational delegation, Philippine parliamentary 
speaker Jose de Venecia, that the time had come for intensified 
creative and patient diplomacy to avoid further deterioration of 
the situation and to ease tensions on the Korean peninsula. 
China will play "a positive role, not a negative role" in 
dealing with the crisis, a Philippine embassy press release 
quoted Jiang as saying. 
  His remarks came as the United Nations started informally 
debating possible sanctions against North Korea which, amid 
suspicions that it is developing a nuclear bomb, has refused to 
allow international inspectors examine crucial parts of its 
nuclear facitilies. China, one of the five permanent members of 
the UN Security Council, has so far rejected the idea of 
sanctions against Pyongyang which it says would only increase 
tensions on the Korean peninsula. 
  Jiang's comments were made in response to a proposal by de 
Valencia for active mediation in the nuclear crisis by China and 
ASEAN. 
  Meanwhile, Jiang also attempted to allay regional concerns 
over China's growing military might. China "will not be a 
threat to its neighbours," Jiang told de Valencia, adding that 
the 20-percent hike China's national defence budget this year to 
52.04 billion yuan (six billion dollars) was the result of 
inflationary adjustments. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

