<F P=100> Northeast Asia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Qian Qichen Reiterates Opposition to Sanctions on DPRK </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Qian Qichen Reiterates Opposition to Sanctions on DPRK </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW0706151694 Tokyo KYODO in English 1446 GMT 7 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0706151694 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Beijing, June 7 KYODO -- Chinese Foreign Minister 
Qian Qichen on Tuesday [7 June] reiterated Beijing's opposition 
to the imposition of sanctions against North Korea to enforce 
the International Atomic Energy Agency's calls for unhampered 
access to North Korean nuclear facilities. 
  "It is not a good way to solve the problem by imposing 
sanctions," China's official XINHUA NEWS AGENCY quoted Qian as 
telling visiting Maltese Foreign Minister Guido de Marco. 
  Qian said China adheres to the stand of maintaining 
stability 
on the Korean Peninsula and making it nuclear free, hoping that 
the nuclear issue will be settled through negotiations, 
according to XINHUA. 
  Discussions about possible punitive steps against North 
Korea 
have intensified at the United Nations since the IAEA said last 
week it can no longer verify whether Pyongyang has diverted 
plutonium after its inspectors were blocked from examining fuel 
rods unloaded at a nuclear reactor. 
  The United States has said it will ask the U.N. Security 
council to impose sanctions on North Korea for its defiance of 
international nuclear safeguards. 
  China, as a permanent member of the key U.N. body, could 
wield its veto to block any measures against its traditional 
ally North Korea. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-25231 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drchi110_d_94007" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-CHI-94-110 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  7 Jun 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> Northeast Asia </F>
<H3> <TI>   DPRK Foreign Minister: North Considering Russian Proposal </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    DPRK Foreign Minister: North Considering Russian Proposal </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   SK0706135294 Beijing China Radio International in Korean 
1110 GMT 7 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> SK0706135294 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing China Radio International </F>
<F P=105>  Korean </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] DPRK Foreign Minister Kim Yong-nam, who is now 
staying in Ukraine, said yesterday that the DPRK would not give 
in to any pressures, nor would the so-called Korean nuclear 
issue be resolved by sanctions, thus denouncing the double 
standard taken by the Western countries regarding the nuclear 
issue. 
  Kim Yong-nam said that regarding the nuclear issue, the 
Western countries, especially the United States, have conducted 
an oppressive policy toward the DPRK -- which is regarded as the 
country that does not obey them -- but instead conducted a 
policy of overlooking the behaviors of other countries that are 
regarded as their friends. 
  Foreign Minister Kim Yong-nam also said that the DPRK is now 
considering Russia's proposal to hold an international 
conference attended by the United States, Russia, China, Japan, 
ROK, and DPRK to resolve the Korean nuclear issue. 
  On the same day, U.S. President Clinton, who is visiting 
European countries, expressed the hope that the DPRK would 
change its view of the nuclear issue, and that it could avoid 
economic sanctions by the international community by 
reconsidering accepting the International Atomic Energy Agency's 
inspections of the DPRK nuclear facilities. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-25232 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drchi110_d_94008" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-CHI-94-110 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  7 Jun 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> Northeast Asia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Wei Jianxing Meets DPRK Trade Union Officials </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Wei Jianxing Meets DPRK Trade Union Officials </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW0706135394 Beijing XINHUA in English 1315 GMT 7 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0706135394 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Beijing, June 7 (XINHUA) -- Wei Jianxing, member of 
the Political Bureau of the Central Committee of the Chinese 
Communist Party (CPC), met here today with U Song-il, president 
of the Central Committee of the General Federation of Trade 
Unions of Korea, and his party. 
  Wei, also president of the All-China Federation of Trade 
Unions (ACFTU) exchanged views with the Korean visitors on 
bilateral ties between China and the Democratic People's 
Republic of Korea (DPRK) and other issues of common interest. 
  The DPRK visitors arrived today for a friendly visit to 
China 
at ACFTU's invitation. 

</TEXT>

