<F P=100> Economic &amp; Agricultural </F>
<H3> <TI>   Securities Commission Denies Chairman To Resign </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Securities Commission Denies Chairman To Resign </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   HK0806055694 Hong Kong SOUTH CHINA MORNING POST (BUSINESS 
POST) in English 8 Jun 94 p 1 </F>

<F P=103> HK0806055694 </F>
<F P=104>  Hong Kong SOUTH CHINA MORNING POST (BUSINESS 
POST) </F>

<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The China Securities Regulatory Commission (CSRC) 
has denied speculation that Liu Hongru will resign as chairman. 
Although no official statement has been issued, a commission 
spokeswoman said the State Council, China's Cabinet, had denied 
reports of Mr Liu stepping down from the job he has held since 
the CSRC was created in 1992. "We confirm that there is no news 
of Mr Liu's resignation. And this confirmation is from the 
State Council," she said, referring to the State Council 
Securities Policies Committee (SCSPC). The CSRC is an executive 
agency of SCSPC. 
  Reports of Mr Liu's departure have been in the Hong Kong 
media in the past few weeks. "Such reports will have an adverse 
impact on the stock market and they should not be issued without 
our confirmation," she added. 
  As the man most identified with China's stock markets, Mr 
Liu 
is instrumental in laying the groundwork for the historic 
listing of mainland corporations in Hong Kong. Another feather 
will be added to his cap when five of the 22 companies in the 
second batch of enterprises slated for overseas flotation head 
for Wall Street next year. 

</TEXT>

