<F P=100> NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political &amp; Social </F>
<H3> <TI>   KYODO Reports Police Release Dissident Lin Xinshu </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    KYODO Reports Police Release Dissident Lin Xinshu </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW0806051794 Tokyo KYODO in English 0458 GMT 8 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0806051794 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Beijing, June 8 KYODO -- Chinese police have 
released a dissident in Fuzhou, Fujian Province after detaining 
him during the June 4 anniversary of the crushing of 
pro-democracy demonstrations in Tiananmen Square in 1989, the 
dissident said Wednesday [8 Jun]. 
  Lin Xinshu, 51, interviewed by telephone, said he believes 
his four-day detention was due to a letter he and nine other 
Fuzhou intellectuals and students sent in late May to the 
Central Committee of the Chinese Communist Party. 
  The letter called for the resignation of Premier Li Peng, 
the 
promotion to prime minister of Vice Premier Zhu Rongji and for 
compensation for those killed when the Chinese Army opened fire 
upon unarmed citizens in the streets of Beijing in 1989. 
  Lin was picked up by plainclothes police on June 2 and 
released Monday, he said. He did not know the whereabouts of 
the other nine signatories. 
  He was forced into exile in Fuzhou from his native Beijing 
in 
1992 and has been detained six times since the 1989 
pro-democracy protests, he said. 
  Three previous letters he sent to the central committee 
demanded the resignation of Li, who signed the martial law order 
of May 1989, Lin said. The letters also called for the 
rehabilitation of ousted Communist Party general secretary Zhao 
Ziyang, he said. 
  The Chinese Government in March ordered a nationwide 
crackdown on political dissent aimed at weeding out those who 
are opposed to the official verdict that the peaceful 
demonstrations in 1989 was a "counterrevolutionary rebellion." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

