<H3> <TI>   U.S. Supports Work of UN Special Envoy to Angola </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    U.S. Supports Work of UN Special Envoy to Angola </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW0806213094 Beijing XINHUA in English 2050 GMT 8 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0806213094 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Luanda, June 8 (XINHUA) -- The United States holds 
that Luanda's agreement to accommodate the rebel National Union 
for the Total Independence of Angola (UNITA) in a future cabinet 
is "an encouraging initiative." 
  Speaking to the local press here today, U.S. Ambassador to 
Angola Joseph Schreiber said the United States, Russia and 
Portugal -- three observer countries of the Angolan peace 
process -- believe the initiative benefits the ongoing peace 
talks in Lusaka, capital of Zambia. 
  Luanda has reportedly agreed to give unita the four 
portfolios of mineral, health, trade and travel, seven 
deputy-minister posts of finance, agriculture, interior, 
defense, social rehabilitation, communication and public works, 
as well as governors of Kuando-Kubango, Uige and Lunda-Sul 
Provinces, deputy governors of several other provinces. 
  The United States firmly supports U.N. Special Envoy to 
Angola Blondin Beye in his efforts to bring lasting peace and 
reconciliation to the Angolan people, the ambassador said. 
  Beye had proposed the government accommodate the UNITA in a 
future cabinet. 
  He said the United States will shoulder 30 percent of U.N. 
expenses for peacekeeping missions in the southern African 
country. 

</TEXT>

