<F P=100> United States &amp; Canada </F>
<H3> <TI>   U.S. Official Defends President Clinton's MFN Decision </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    U.S. Official Defends President Clinton's MFN Decision </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW0906054194 Beijing XINHUA in English 0513 GMT 9 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0906054194 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Washington, June 8 (XINHUA) -- A senior U.S. 
Administration official said Wednesday [8 June] that president 
Clinton's decision to unconditionally renew China's 
most-favored-nation [MFN] trading status will result in a 
long-term, mature and evolving relationship with what is 
becoming one of the world's most powerful economic forces. 
  Speaking at the annual meeting of the U.S.-China Business 
Council, Bowman Cutter, deputy assistant to the president for 
economic policy, said, "we will oppose any attempts in Congress 
to reverse this decision." 
  "In very plain words, this is an issue we should get behind 
us...it's time now to move toward the definition and the 
development of our next steps," he added. 
  He said that the U.S. relationship with China must include 
"full engagement" and "constant dialogue." 
  "A growing economic relationship is anticipated," he 
stressed. 
  However, he cautioned, "we should be realistic about the 
economic relationship... There will be disagreements but we 
think that a mature and growing relationship can work through 
them." 
  He described this relationship as one that "must be 
characterized by a mutual recognition of strategic importance." 
  Cutter also indicated that the U.S. will "insist upon a 
continued focus on democracy and human rights" in its relations 
with China. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

