<F P=100> Northeast Asia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Qian, Han Discuss Nuclear Issue </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Qian, Han Discuss Nuclear Issue </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW0906092694 Beijing XINHUA in English 0915 GMT 9 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0906092694 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Beijing, June 9 (XINHUA) -- Chinese Vice-Premier and 
Foreign Minister Qian Qichen had a working meeting here today 
with Han Sung-chu, minister of foreign affairs of the Republic 
of Korea (ROK). 
  Han briefed Qian on the latest developments centering on the 
nuclear issue on the Korean peninsula. 
  Stating China's point of view on the current situation, Qian 
pointed out that, with the efforts of the parties concerned, not 
long ago the development on the issue was in a positive 
direction. 
  But recently, he continued, due to disputes between the 
International Atomic Energy Agency and the Democratic People's 
Republic of Korea about the inspection of the replacement of 
fuel rods the situation has taken a sudden turn, and the Chinese 
side has shown much concern about this. 
  He stated that the Chinese side advocates two basic targets 
for efforts to solve the issue: the denuclearization of the 
Korean peninsula and the safeguarding of peace and stability 
there. 
  He said that these targets are in the fundamental interests 
of all the countries in Northeast Asia. 
  Facing the current difficulty, Qian pointed out, it is 
particularly necessary for the concerned parties to keep calm 
and restraint, and not to close the door to negotiations rashly. 
  He stated, "We call on all the parties directly concerned to 
make further efforts to start talks so as to leave room and keep 
possibilities alive for the settlement of the issue." 
  Qian pointed out that sanctions can not help solve the 
issue; 
on the contrary, sanctions may lead to results that none of the 
concerned parties is willing to see. 
  Han arrived here yesterday evening on a working visit. 

</TEXT>

