<F P=100> Northeast Asia </F>
<H3> <TI>   More on DPRK Nuclear Issue </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    More on DPRK Nuclear Issue </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   HK0906091894 Beijing ZHONGGUO XINWEN SHE in Chinese 0808 GMT 
9 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> HK0906091894 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing ZHONGGUO XINWEN SHE </F>
<F P=105>  Chinese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By reporter Li Wei (2621 0251)] </F>
  [Text] Beijing, 9 Jun (ZHONGGUO XINWEN SHE) -- China's 
Vice Premier and Foreign Minister Qian Qichen told ROK Foreign 
Minister Han Sung-chu this morning: China holds that two basic 
targets should be set for the settlement of the issue of North 
Korea's nuclear fuel, that is, promoting denuclearization in the 
Korean peninsula and safeguarding peace and stability there. 
China considers these two targets are in conformity with the 
fundamental interests of all countries in northeast Asia. 
  The Chinese and ROK foreign ministers held a working meeting 
here this morning. Han Sung-chu gave an account of the recent 
new developments of the nuclear issue on the Korean peninsula. 
Qian Qichen expounded China's views on the current situation. 
  Thanks to efforts made by various parties, Qian Qichen said 
that the situation at the previous stage had developed in a 
positive direction. Because of differences between the 
International Atomic Energy Agency and the DPRK on inspections 
of the nuclear fuel rods, the situation had deteriorated. China 
is deeply concerned about the situation. 
  In the face of the current difficulties, Qian Qichen pointed 
out that the parties concerned should, in particular, keep calm 
and remain restrained and should not shut the door to 
negotiations. 
  Qian said that China had appealed to the parties concerned 
to 
continue to make efforts to restart talks to leave room for the 
possibility of a settlement of the issue. 
  Qian also pointed out that sanctions would not help solve 
the 
problem. On the contrary, they might lead to consequences which 
no one wished to see. 
  Han Sung-chu arrived in Beijing on the evening of 8 June for 
a working visit. He will leave for home on the afternoon of 9 
June. 

</TEXT>

