<H3> <TI>   INTERFAX Reports Last Russian Warships Leave Latvia </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    INTERFAX Reports Last Russian Warships Leave Latvia </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW0206030294 Beijing XINHUA in English 0234 GMT 2 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0206030294 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Moscow, June 1 (XINHUA) -- Russia withdrew the last 
three of its warships from Latvia today in accordance with a 
plan for troops withdrawal from the Baltic country. 
  The INTERFAX NEWS AGENCY reported that the three warships of 
the Russian Baltic Fleet left Liepaja Port of Latvia for 
Baltiysk Port in Russia. 
  Only a dozen Navy workers stayed behind to deal with 
remaining financial issues, INTERFAX said. 
  Latvian Prime Minister Valdis Birkavs said at a ceremony to 
mark the departure that Latvia and Russia are now embarking on a 
road of normal good-neighborly relations. 
  He said this can be proved by the Russian Navy's withdrawal 
today and Russia's granting of Latvia the most-favored-nation 
trade status, which has already taken effect. 
  In the wake of the Navy's pullout, the other services of the 
Russian Armed Forces will also complete their withdrawal by 
August 31. 

</TEXT>

