<F P=100> Science &amp; Technology </F>
<H3> <TI>   Urges Contributing to Economy </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Urges Contributing to Economy </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW0806173494 Beijing XINHUA in English 1604 GMT 8 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0806173494 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Beijing, June 8 (XINHUA) -- The Chinese science and 
technology community should make decisive contributions to a 
sustaining development of the national economy in the next 50 
years, said Song Jian, director of the State Science and 
Technology Commission. 
  Speaking at today's closing ceremony of the general meetings 
of the Chinese Academy of Sciences (CAS) and the Chinese Academy 
of Engineering (CAE), Song said that the community should 
continue its efforts to help establish a scientific and 
democratic policy-making system. 
  In the main battlefield of the economic drive, all science 
and technology departments must do their part to help solve the 
problems which come up in the development of the country's 
industry, agriculture and the service industries, said Song, who 
is a state councillor. 
  "Such departments are also expected to help spread the use 
of 
new and advanced scientific results in order to raise the 
productivity of all industries and lead the rural and township 
enterprises onto a healthy development track and upgrade their 
technologies," he said. 
  He said that the country's science and technology sector 
must 
strive to develop environment-protection technology and develop 
as well as promote pollution-free production processes and 
methods so as to reduce and, eventually, halt the emission of 
pollutants. 
  "Scientists and technologists must contribute more to the 
protection of the environment on which people of all 
nationalities live and advance," the official noted. 
  To rule out possible mistakes in major policy-making, the 
whole process must involve the active participation of science 
and technology departments, Song said. 
  He said that the Chinese science and technology world must 
map out its ninth five-year plan and a 15-year development 
program on the basis of science and democracy. 
  The country's science and technology community should target 
some scientific and engineering projects that have a direct 
bearing on social and economic development. 
  He also said that China should train a large number of young 
scientists and engineers for the next century and set up 
well-equiped research institutions and key national labs. 
  From now on, the science and technology community should 
also 
reform itself so as to open wider to the outside world and 
expand international cooperation, Song said. 
  He urged the CAS and CAE, China's two top scientific bodies, 
to cooperate closely with each other while tapping their 
respective strengths. 
  "This will help develop the national economy and bolster the 
overall national strength," he said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-25309 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drchi111_l_94004" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-CHI-94-111 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  9 Jun 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> Science &amp; Technology </F>
<H3> <TI>   Urges Exerting Greater Influence </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Urges Exerting Greater Influence </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   HK0906035894 Beijing CHINA DAILY in English 9 Jun 94 p 1 </F>
<F P=103> HK0906035894 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing CHINA DAILY </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By He Jun: "Scientists Called On for Greater Influence"] </F>
  [Text] China's top science and technology administrator has 
urged the country's newly-nominated academicians to actively 
involve themselves in the government's decisionmaking process. 
  Song Jian, State Councillor and Minister of the State 
Science 
and Technology Commission, made the request yesterday in Beijing 
at the closing session of the inaugural meeting of the 
newly-established Chinese Academy of Engineering (CAE) and the 
seventh academician conference of the Chinese Academy of 
Sciences (CAS). 
  He asked the scholars of the two organizations to give more 
suggestions and advice for the drafting of the country's Ninth 
Five-Year Plan (1996-2000) and the 15-year plan that sets goals 
to 2010. 
  The plans are expected to be finished by the end of next 
year 
and be submitted for approval at the March session of the 
National People's Congress in 1996. 
  China's population will continuously expand during the next 
40 years to reach 1.6 billion to 1.7 billion, Song said. 
  Therefore, by the 2030's or 2040's, China's grain output 
needs to increase by 50 per cent just to ensure that the current 
modest supply remains level; electric energy production should 
expand 14-fold to reach the current per capita standard of 
moderately-developed countries; and all agricultural and 
industrial sectors and infrastructural facilities should be 
greatly expanded, he added. 
  China's modernization requires the constant efforts of all 
social sectors, especially science, for at least the next half 
century, he said. 
  Song stressed the importance of developing pollution-free 
production, reducing waste discharges, protecting the ecological 
balance, and establishing an environmental protection industry. 
  He also promised that the government will try its best to 
increase its investment in science and technology. 
  The total input from all social sectors in research and 
development should account for more than 1.5 per cent of the 
gross national product by the end of the century, instead of the 
current 0.7 per cent, he said. 
  At yesterday's session, the CAS also announced the 
appointment of its first group of foreign academicians. 
  The 14 foreign scientists include Derek Barton and Joseph 
Needham of Britain, and Peter Raven and Herbert Simon of the 
United States. 
  The others are all Chinese-American scientists, including 
the 
Nobel Prize winners Samuel Chao Chung Ting, Chen Ning Yang, and 
Tsungdao Lee. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-25310 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drchi111_l_94005" </HT>


<HEADER>
