<F P=100> Economic &amp; Agricultural </F>
<H3> <TI>   Arbitration Commission Flooded With Work </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Arbitration Commission Flooded With Work </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   HK0906043694 Beijing CHINA DAILY in English 9 Jun 94 p 2 </F>
<F P=103> HK0906043694 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing CHINA DAILY </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By Wang Yong: "Firms Put More Faith in Arbiters"] </F>
  [Text] Officials expect China to remain the world's largest 
commercial arbitration centre, indicating that foreign firms 
have a growing reliance on Chinese mediators. 
  More than 250 cases flooded the China International Economic 
and Trade Arbitration Commission (Cietac) by the end of May. 
Cietac predicts it will handle nearly 600 cases before the year 
is out. 
  Cietac handled 486 cases last year more than any other 
international centre. 
  "More and more Chinese and foreign companies are willing to 
resort to Cietac for settling their business disputes," said Zhu 
Jianlin, deputy secretary general of Cietac, at a briefing for 
the upcoming International Commercial Arbitration Legislation 
Conference. 
  The conference, to be held in Beijing on June 22 and 23, 
should further link China's business arbitration with 
international standards. 
  Decisions made in China are now honoured and enforced in 
more 
than 90 countries and regions. 
  In the past, many foreigners fled to other international 
arbitrators whenever disputes arose about things like wording in 
joint-venture contracts or poor shipments of materials. 
  Now the world is focusing on particular Chinese mediation 
practices because of its increasing importance in international 
commercial arbitration. 
  China has successfully combined arbitration with its 
traditional thinking of mediation. 
  Chinese arbitrators help the disputing parties come to 
mutual 
agreement and reconciliation, easing tensions rather than 
furthering the anger. 
  But in many nations, arbitrators must decide who wins and 
who 
loses, no matter how furious a party might be. 
  The international conference will provide the foreign 
experts 
with a perfect perch for examining the Chinese experience. 
  More than 300 Chinese and foreign arbitration and trade 
experts will attend the conference, the first of its kind in 
China and the entire Asia-Pacific region. 
  China hopes the event will help its re-entry into the 
General 
Agreement on Tariffs and Trade (Gatt); other parts of the world 
will see at first hand the progress China has made toward 
meeting international norms in economic activities. 
  The conference is being organized by Cietac and the 
International Council of Commercial Arbitration. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

