<DOCNO> FBIS4-25330 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drchi111_k_94004" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-CHI-94-111 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  8 Jun 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political &amp; Social </F>
<H3> <TI>   Li Peng Solicits Opinions on Education Matters </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Li Peng Solicits Opinions on Education Matters </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW0806152894 Beijing XINHUA in English 1503 GMT 8 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0806152894 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Beijing, June 8 (XINHUA) -- Chinese Premier Li Peng 
today had a discussion at Zhongnanhai -- the government seat in 
the capital -- to seek a wide swathe of opinions on education 
matters. 
  Among the people he was consulting on a report he would make 
to a national education working conference later this month were 
leaders of China's eight non-communist parties. 
  Also taking part in the discussion were representatives of 
the All-China Federation of Industry And commerce, and people 
without party affiliations. 
  The national education working conference is the second such 
meeting convened by the Chinese Communist Party Central 
Committee and the State Council since China started its policy 
of reform and opening to the world in the late 1970s. 
  The meeting is considered to be very important for solving 
problems in China's educational reform and development. 
  The people taking part in the discussion gave much advice 
and 
expressed their opinions on how to popularize the nine-year 
compulsory education system, how to develop vocational education 
and education for adults, and how to increase the input to 
education. 

</TEXT>

